When Stanley finally found him in 1872, he uttered the phrase, 'Dr. Livingstone, I presume?' - and people have been repeating the quote, or variations of it, ever since.
157.story: The Stanley and Livingstone story was huge news at the time. One fan of the reports was Hamilton landowner Charles Mills, who renamed a portion of Markland Street in appreciation of Stanley's accomplishment, according to the book Hamilton Street Names by Margaret Houghton.

158.name: Studholme Road
158.desc: The road was named after labour leader Allan Studholme in 1959, when the city works yard was opened beside the golf course. The stub nearest Aberdeen has been in existence since 1895, when the former TH&B yard and freight office opened.
158.story: Studholme (1846 to 1919) was a labour leader and politician from the 1880s until his death. He acted for the workers during the bitter 1906 HSR streetcar strike and won a seat that year in the Ontario legislature in a byelection for Hamilton East. He was the first trade unionist elected to the legislature and held that seat until his death. He championed the eight-hour work day, a minimum wage and was involved in the passing of the Workmen's Compensation Act. He introduced a bill in 1910 to give women the right to vote. Women in Ontario won that right in 1917.

159.name: Studholme Road
159.desc: George Summers (1865-1941) was a theatre manager, actor and comedian who established his Summers Theatre on Hamilton Mountain in the early 1900s.
159.story: The popular 700-seat theatre attracted more than 70,000 patrons from May to September each year over its 11-year run. Patrons would travel to the Summers Theatre using the incline railway near the Wentworth Stairs. In December 1914, the theatre burned to the ground and was never replaced.

160.name: A.M. Cunningham Elementary School
160.desc: Alexander McKenzie Cunningham (1863-1926) was a local photographer and Hamilton Board of Education trustee.
160.story: After being elected trustee for the Hamilton board, he became chairman and pushed for standardizing school buildings to save costs. He set out to photograph every school, class and staff member in the board, something that was completed the year after he died. Those photographs have become a cherished collection at the board's Educational Archives and Heritage Centre.

161.name: A.N. Bourns Science Building
161.desc: Arthur Newcombe Bourns, now 93, is a former president of McMaster who worked as a chemistry professor and served in various senior administration posts at the university.
161.story: Bourns came to McMaster in 1947 as an assistant professor and became a full professor six years later. From there he was promoted to chairman, dean and vice-president of science and engineering. From 1972 to 1980, he served as president.

162.name: Adelaide Hoodless School
162.desc: Adelaide Hoodless was a strong advocate for women and children and a proponent of including domestic science courses in the city's elementary schools.
162.story: One of Hamilton's oldest elementary schools, Adelaide Hoodless opened in 1911 - a year after the death of its namesake.

163.name: Billy Green Elementary School
163.desc: Billy Green (1794-1877) is remembered as a hero from the Battle of Stoney Creek in 1813.
163.story: During the War of 1812, Green is reputed to have tipped off the British about an American encampment in Stoney Creek and then led them to the site. This allowed the British to make a successful surprise attack in the early hours of June 6, 1813 during the famous battle. However, more recently, a book by former Spectator reporter James Elliott, Strange Fatality, questioned the story, saying it was undoubtedly a tall tale inspired by the exploits of Laura Secord or Paul Revere.

164.name: Buchanan Park School
164.desc: Sir Isaac Buchanan was a well-known, 19th-century merchant and politician.
164.story: The school and park were named after Buchanan, who in the 1850s built the celebrated Auchmar house on a Mountain property now at the intersection of West 5th and Fennell Avenue. He also established the 13th Battalion of the militia, later renamed the Royal Hamilton Light Infantry.

165.name: Dr. J. Edgar Davey school
165.desc: It was named for a local doctor who, starting in 1923, served the Hamilton Board of Education for close to three decades - principally as its chief medical officer. In 1940, he was named the city's chief medical officer of health, and in 1962, he was named Hamilton's citizen of the year.
165.story: The school absorbed students from the former King Edward and Cannon Street schools when it opened in 1971. Rebuilt in 2010 as part of the Hamilton-Wentworth District School Board's revitalization plan, it serves one of the most impoverished urban areas in the country.

166.name: J. L. Grightmire Arena
166.desc: James Louis Grightmire (1891-1963) was known for bus transportation and constructing sports facilities in Dundas.
166.story: Bert Edwards, a former mayor of Dundas, said in the early 1960s that 'in Dundas, if you swim, play golf, curl or even ride on the bus, you have reason to be grateful to James Grightmire.' Grightmire established a bus line between Hamilton and Dundas after the First World War. He also was a founder of the Dundas Golf and Curling Club, and was quoted as saying 'the course was built for the working man with fees to be kept as reasonable as possible.' He was involved in building the arena that bears his name. The facility was used for an NHL exhibition game in 2010 after Dundas was named Hockeyville in a national contest by the CBC.
166.caption: City of Hamilton employee works on the ice surface.

167.name: The Gary Proctor Building
167.desc: Gary Proctor (1945-1967) was the son of Wilfred Proctor, who erected the building in the early 1970s.
167.story: Wilfred Proctor was known for running the ARC School of Welding from that site. After his son Gary died at 22 - apparently after being injured in a hockey game - he built the three-storey building at John and Wilson and named it after the son so the young man's name would be remembered. The Proctor family long ago sold the building, but the name endures.
167.caption: The Gary Proctor building at the corner of John and Wilson Sts.

168.name: Jimmy Thompson Pool
168.desc: Thompson (1906 to 1966) was a competitive swimmer, as well as an aquatics coach and teacher.
168.story: A member of the Canadian Olympic swimming team that competed in the 1928 Games in Amsterdam, he won a bronze medal for the 880-yard freestyle race. In 1932, he came to Hamilton, where he worked as an aquatics coach and swimming instructor. Over the years, he taught tens of thousands of young people how to swim in classes that would sometimes see more than 300 students.
168.caption: The Jimmy Thompson pool circa 1940.

169.name: Bishop Tonnos apartment
169.desc: The Most Reverend Anthony Tonnos was Hamiltonâ€™s bishop from 1984 to 2010.
169.story: Tonnos was born and raised in Port Colborne. He was ordained as Hamiltonâ€™s auxiliary bishop in 1983, and became its bishop the following year. He served for 26 years as leader of the local Catholic community until retiring at age 75, as is customary for bishops. He was succeeded by Douglas Crosby.
169.caption: Bishop Anothony Tonnos receives a round of applause following mass at St. Mary's Cathedral on Park St. North in Hamilton on November 7, 2010, his last official function as Bishop for the diocese.

170.name: Brian Timmis Stadium
170.desc: Brian Timmis (1899 to 1971) was a Canadian Football League star in the 1920s and '30s.
170.story: Timmis played mostly with the Hamilton Tigers and the Ottawa Rough Riders in an era when players served on both the offensive and defensive teams. He later coached the Hamilton Flying Wildcats and was inducted into the Canadian Football Hall of Fame and Canada's Sports Hall of Fame. The Tigers and Wildcats merged in 1950 to become the Hamilton Tiger-Cats.
170.caption: Hamiltonâ€™s amateur athletes play at Brian Timmis Stadium in 1974.

171.name: The John Weir Foote V.C. Armouries
171.desc: John Weir Foote was a chaplain with the RHLI during the Second World War, a Victoria Cross recipient and later in life served as an MPP in Durham.
171.story: Foote received the Victoria Cross for his heroic efforts helping wounded soldiers on the beach of Dieppe in the ill-fated raid by the Allied forces in 1942.
171.caption: Honorary Major john Weir Foote on February 12, 1946.

172.name: Mark Preece Family House
172.desc: Dr. Mark Preece (1959 to 1997) was an ICU physician at the Hamilton General Hospital who died of complications from melanoma.
172.story: Preece underwent experimental cancer treatment in Pittsburgh in 1997, where his family stayed in a special residence for families of patients. After he died, family and friends thought Hamilton could use a similar facility. After more than a dozen years of fundraising and a major fire in 2008, the facility finally opened in 2011.
172.caption: The Mark Preece Family House.

173.name: The John Sopinka Courthouse
173.desc: John Sopinka (1933-1997) was a Supreme Court of Canada justice.
173.story: Sopinka came to Hamilton as a boy in 1939, later moving to Stoney Creek where he graduated from Saltfleet high school. While attending law school, he played football with the Toronto Argonauts and the Montreal Alouettes. His appointment to the Supreme Court in 1988 was a surprise to many because he had no prior experience as a judge with a lower court.
173.caption: The John Sopinka Courthouse.

174.name: Clappisonâ€™s Corners
174.desc: Henry Clappison operated a couple of hotels in what was a thriving stage coach stop in the mid to late 19th century.
174.story: As the automobile became more popular through the early decades of the 20th century, the road network expanded including Highway 6, which broke through the escarpment in what came to be known as the Clappison Cut. It ushered in a new era for the community and spelled an end to the horse and buggy community.
174.caption: Clappisonâ€™s Corners looking east from just west of Highway 6.

175.name: R.L. Hyslop School
175.desc: Robert L. Hyslop was a longtime Stoney Creek educator.
175.story: R.L. Hyslop School was built in 1966 to replace an old and overcrowded building constructed in 1880 as a two-room schoolhouse and expanded several times over the years. It was known as S.S. #3 Saltfleet or Stoney Creek School. In 1958, the name was changed to remember Hyslop, who had been its principal from 1918 to 1958.
175.caption: Grade 7 and 8 class of 1940.

176.name: Ray Lowes Side Trail
176.desc: Lowes (1911 to 2007) is credited with founding the Bruce Trail.
176.story: He loved the Niagara Escarpment and believed a good way to protect it would be to create a public footpath along its length so people could appreciate its beauty and ecological value. Today, there are more than 1,200 kilometres of main and side trails.
176.caption: Ray Lowes, pictured here in 1992, is father of the Bruce Trail, which officially opened in 1967.

177.name: Irving Zucker Sculpture Garden
177.desc: Irving Zucker (1920-2002) was well-known for his philanthropy in Hamilton.
177.story: Zucker founded CHIQ broadcasting, then CHAM Radio and eventually put together a network of radio stations in Ontario and Eastern Canada. By the 1980s, he had sold his broadcasting interests and devoted himself to collecting art and philanthropy. The sculpture garden contains several sculptures that Zucker donated.
177.caption: From left, Louise Dompierre, Irving Zucker, Sandra Witelson

178.name: Pauline Johnson Elementary School
178.desc: Pauline Johnson (1861 to 1913) is a well-known First Nations poet.
178.story: The school named in honour of the Six Nations-born poet, best known for her performances in both traditional native and Victorian dress, opened in 1967 and now shares land with Cardinal Heights Middle School. Johnson was the first native female writer in Canada to be honoured with a commemorative stamp.
178.caption: A file photo of Pauline Johnson

179.name: Dr. John Seaton Elementary School
179.desc: It was named after a prominent doctor who served the former community of Beverly Township from 1920 to 1959. Seaton actively promoted youth sports programs and helped co-found the Ontario Rural Hockey Association and the Ontario Rural Softball Association in the early 1930s. He served in the medical corps of the Canadian Army toward the end of the First World War and held the rank of captain.
179.story: The school was opened in 1969 by the former Beverly Township School Board. The school has about 250 students ranging from junior kindergarten to Grade 8. It was renovated in 2010 when Sheffield School closed.

180.name: R.A. Riddell Elementary School
180.desc: Riddell, who died in 1967 at the age of 71, was a longtime education administrator with the Hamilton board of education.
180.story: He was a teacher, then a principal before working as an inspector from 1938 to 1944, director of public schools from 1944 to 1953 and was the first director of education from 1953 to 1961.

181.name: George R. Robinson Bandshell
181.desc: For nearly a half century, George R. Robinson (1840 to 1917) was bandmaster of the 13th Battalion, now known as the Royal Hamilton Light Infantry.
181.story: The military band was struggling before Robinson took it over in 1869. But within a short time he managed to build it into a well-disciplined touring machine that travelled across the continent, spreading word about the battalion and the City of Hamilton.

182.name: Wilcox Street
182.desc: Charles Seward Wilcox became the first president of the Steel Company of Canada (Stelco) in 1910. In 1916, he became chairman of the board, a position he held until he died in 1938.
182.story: Wilcox donated land on Cannon Street for a playground and also gave generously to the sanatorium. In recognition, the Wilcox Pavilion in Chedoke Hospital was named after him. In 1930, Harvey Lane, adjacent to Stelco, was renamed Wilcox Street in his honour, according to the book Hamilton Street Names.

183.name: Witherspoon Street
183.desc: Witherspoon Street is in Dundas and runs east-west between Market Street North and Melville Street.
183.story: Patriarch Alexander Witherspoon died before ever setting foot in Dundas. According to the book Hamilton Street Names, he took a purse of gold in Scotland for inventing an improvement to watchmaking and bought a farm west of Dundas. The Dundas Valley Golf and Curling Club now occupies part of this farm. During the ocean crossing, he fell ill, but when he arrived in Hamilton he wanted to walk to his farm. He collapsed en route and died four days later. His wife sold the farm and built a house on Hatt Street. The couple had 10 children.

184.name: Yeoville Neighbourhood
184.desc: Sir James Lucas Yeo (1782 to 1818), was a British naval commander in the War of 1812, in charge of the Great Lakes fleet.
184.story: Among his accomplishments in the War of 1812 were successfully blockading the American fleet in Sackett's Harbour, Lake Ontario, for months and capturing Oswego, now part of New York State, in 1814. After the war he served in the British Navy on the West African coast and died at sea.

185.name: Thorpe Street
185.desc: Jacob Thorpe was a brewery owner who moved to Dundas in the 1820s. He died in 1932 of cholera.
185.story: According to the book Hamilton Street Names, the street (formerly called Church Street) was changed in 1827 after the wealthy Thorpe donated $10 to improvements to nearby roads to improve transportation in the small town. The road was partially closed in 1878.

186.name: Thorpe Street
186.desc: Twenty Road is named for Twenty Mile Creek, which has its headwaters in Glanbrook.
186.story: Twenty Road was known in the early part of the 20th century as Powerline Road. Hamilton Street Names says this was due to hydro lines that ran south of the road. The headwaters of Twenty Mile Creek are in the northwest part of the former township. It might have been renamed because of the existence of Powerline Road, which runs between Ancaster and Brantford. It has hydro lines running east of the road. Twenty Creek runs east into Niagara, spills over the escarpment at Ball's Falls and empties into Lake Ontario at Jordan Harbour.

187.name: Terryberry Library
187.desc: In 1810, William Terryberry opened the Terryberry Inn, near where the library stands today.
187.story: Stofel Durenberger (1714 to 1766) came to North America from Germany in 1738 and his name was anglicized to Stephen Terryberry. His grandson William moved to the Hamilton area in the early 1800s, opening the inn that was a popular stopover for people travelling by stagecoach between Niagara and Ancaster. The inn was demolished in 1897.

188.name: Albemarle Street
188.desc: William Coutts Keppel, Viscount Bury was the only son and heir of the Sixth Earl of Albemarle.
188.story: He was appointed Civil Secretary and Superintendent of Indian Affairs in Upper Canada in 1854 under Sir Allan MacNab, who was prime minister of pre-Confederation Canada at the time. The following year, he married Sophia Mary MacNab, daughter of Sir Allan. Together they had 10 children, and their descendants include Camilla, the Duchess of Cornwall.

189.name: Bull's Lane
189.desc: Canon George Armstrong Bull (1828-1909) was an Anglican minister and son of George Perkins Bull, the founder of the Gazette newspaper in Hamilton that later joined with The Spectator in 1850.
189.story: Bull built a large house he called The Cliff on property near Bull's Lane inherited from his father. He had quite an interest in history, and according to Hamilton local history author Margaret Houghton, Bull is credited with discovering the original photograph of Laura Secord.

190.name: Burloak Drive
190.desc: A hybrid of Burlington and Oakville that marks the boundary between the cities.
190.story: The road was originally called the Town Line, but that was considered too confusing. In 1966, it was changed to more literally reflect where Burlington and Oakville meet.

191.name: Cummins Lane
191.desc: Titus Cummins, a Justice of the Peace and postmaster, among other things, founded Cumminsville, a hamlet south of Kilbride, in the 1800s.
191.story: The City of Burlington's planning department decided to commemorate Cumminsville by naming this street after the former hamlet's founder, according to the book Burlington Streets, What's Behind a Name?

192.name: Darlene Court
192.desc: It is named after Darlene Andrews, who worked as a draftsperson for the City of Burlington.
192.story: According to Burlingtonâ€™s Streets, by the Burlington Historical Society, Andrews was on contract with the city when she was presented with a street plan by a developer in 1981. When told a name was required for the street, he asked Andrews what her name was. After she told him, the developer responded: 'That will do.' One of the businesses on the court is Ultramatic Sleep of Canada, the adjustable bed company. Burlington bed baron Ron Patterson sold it in 2007.

193.name: Dovercourt Avenue
193.desc: Dovercourt, England, is the burial spot of Burlington's Reginald Bullock, who was killed in the First World War.
193.story: Landowner Nora Bullock of Burlington sold the property to a developer in 1956 on the condition that the street would be named to honour her son, Reginald, who was killed in action in 1918 and was buried at Dovercourt.

194.name: Dr. Frank J. Hayden Secondary School
194.desc: Burlingtonâ€™s newest high school, set to open its doors this fall in the Alton area, is named after Frank Hayden, who helped create the Special Olympics, which began in 1968. The program now provides training and competition for more than three million athletes in more than 170 countries.
194.story: A Burlington resident for 37 years, Hayden has received numerous honorary degrees and awards for his research and contributions to the quality of life of people with intellectual disabilities through sport. From 1975 to 1981 he was director of the School of Physical Education and Athletics at Mac.

195.name: Elizabeth Street
195.desc: There are differing views about the origin of the name.
195.story: According to the Burlington Historical Society, Elizabeth refers to the youngest daughter of Chief Joseph Brant or an Elizabeth Kerns who cared for the sick and injured, helping out a local doctor.

196.name: Gordie Tapp Crescent
196.desc: Tapp, 91, who lives in Burlington, is a longtime broadcaster and entertainer and is best known for his more than two decades as a performer and writer on the American television program Hee Haw.
196.story: Tapp, who began his career as a radio broadcaster in Niagara Falls, has received numerous accolades in his career including a lifetime achievement award from the Hamilton Music Awards in 2012.

197.name: Grenallen Drive
197.desc: Gren Allen was a longtime reporter at The Hamilton Spectator who died in 1981 at the age of 62.
197.story: The Spectator has had hundreds of reporters over the years, but it seems that only one has managed to get a byline on a street sign. His name was Gren Allen. For decades he covered news in Burlington and Milton and then one day in the early '80s, he found himself at a Burlington council meeting where councillors didn't like a list of street names put forward by a developer for a new subdivision. Stymied for alternatives, a councillor looked over at the press table and said there's a street name for you - Gren Allen.

198.name: Hadfield Court
198.desc: Lieutenant Colonel Chris Hadfield was the first Canadian to fly as a NASA mission specialist.
198.story: Hadfield, who is living in space and serving as commander of the International Space Station, is from Milton. The street was named to honour his achievement as the first Canadian to set foot on Mir, the Russian space station, and the first to operate the Canadarm robotic manipulator system in orbit.

199.name: Jackson Street
199.desc: Hamilton Street Names says the street is named after Edward Jackson, a wealthy businessman and active Methodist who helped found the Wesleyan Ladiesâ€™s College (1861-1890) on the site of what today is the Royal Connaught.
199.story: Jackson came to the area in 1828 and opened the Hamilton Tin Factory. It was located on Catharine Street and produced a variety of tin goods and then stoves. He was also a director of the Bank of Hamilton and a partner in an iron foundry in London, Ont. He founded the unique womenâ€™s college with other city Methodists.

200.name: Kerns Road
200.desc: It was named for the Kerns family, who moved to the area in the early 1800s.
200.story: The book Burlington's Streets by the Burlington Historical Society says Jacob Kerns owned 85 hectares of land - the west boundary is the north end of Kerns Road. Nicholas Kerns had a farm on the east side of Brant Street, from the Queen Elizabeth Way to just north of Upper Middle Road. The southern end of Kerns Road was once the laneway to the farm of Wilber Kerns. The book says the road was named in 1968.

201.name: Kilmer Drive
201.desc: Sergeant Alfred Joyce Kilmer (1889-1918) was a poet and author born in New Jersey is the United States.
201.story: Kilmer died from a sniper's bullet in the First World War. He was awarded the French Croix de Guerre honour for bravery.

202.name: LaSalle Park
202.desc: The park is named for French explorer RenÃ©-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle, who is believed to have landed at the site in 1669. It was built in 1915 by the Hamilton Parks Board and initially called Wabasso Park. It was renamed LaSalle Park in 1926. The park is leased to Burlington.
202.story: La Salle (1643 to 1687) came to New France (Montreal) in 1667 and became interested in exploring when told by natives of rivers and valleys farther west. He led three expeditions in the late 1600s, covered much of the Great Lakes basin and U.S. Midwest and found the mouth of the Mississippi River. He claimed what became known as Louisiana for King Louis XIV. He was killed on an expedition in what is now Texas.

203.name: Lockhart Road
203.desc: John Lockhart, who died in 1986 at the age of 93, was a mayor of Burlington from 1957 to 1961.
203.story: A few years after retiring from a 35-year career as a principal and teacher at Central Public High School in Burlington, he was urged to run for mayor. And while his time at the post was relatively short - four years - he is remembered for quickly overcoming his lack of political experience and running a smooth council.

204.name: Aberdeen Avenue
204.desc: Hamilton Street Names says the avenue was named in 1888 for Lord and Lady Aberdeen.
204.story: It was previously called Concession Street. Their lordships lived in Hamilton with their four children on Bay Street South towards the end of the 19th century. They opened the Hamilton Public Library in 1890 and visited numerous schools. Lord John Campbell Gordon died in 1934 and his wife, Lady Ishbel Maria Gordon, died in 1939.

205.name: Rymal Road
205.desc: Hamilton Street Names says this piece of the former Highway 53 on the Hamilton Mountain was named after the Rymal family, one of the first to settle on the Mountain.
205.story: William Rymal arrived in 1788 and settled on land around what today is Mohawk Road and Upper Paradise Road. He is believed to have established the first church and the first cemetery on the mountain. St. Peterâ€™s cemetery is just east of Westcliffe Mall. His son Jacob later served as MPP for Wentworth County and his grandson Joseph served as MP for Wentworth South.

206.name: Borer's Falls Conservation Area
206.desc: The Dundas falls and conservation area on Valley Road is named after a family which used the falls to operate a saw mill.
206.story: The City of Waterfalls website says the family operated the saw mill for nearly a century. John Borer Sr. came to the area in 1865 with his wife and four children. He died in 1900. The mill operated on the creek until 1949. It is also known as the Rock Chapel Falls. Borerâ€™s sons were a blacksmith and a farmer. The attractiveness of the Falls has made it a feature on postcards since the early 1900s.

207.name: Caroline Street
207.desc: The downtown Hamilton street was named after the daughter of a wealthy man who owned large tracts of land in the city.
207.story: Caroline was the daughter of Peter Hess. The Dictionary of Hamilton Biography says he owned the land west of present day Bay Street to Queen Street, stretching from Aberdeen Street to almost near the bay. This was in the early 19th Century. When the land was subdivided, his daughter got a street named after her and he lent his name to Hess Street and Peter Street.

208.name: Catharine Street
208.desc: The downtown street was named after the daughter of one of Hamiltonâ€™s founders.
208.story: Catharine was the daughter of Nathaniel Hughson. He gave his name to Hughson Street and named other streets after family members, James Street (son) and Rebecca Street (wife).

209.name: H.G. Brewster Pool
209.desc: The Winona pool at Orchard Park High School is named after Harry G. Brewster.
209.story: Brewster was a school trustee who was a member of the construction committee and worked hard on making the project a reality in the mid-1960s. He died suddenly of a heart attack during that time.

210.name: Dean Vista Parkette
210.desc: The Winona area parkette is named after Gordon Dean, who served as Stoney Creek mayor and as an Ontario cabinet minister.
210.story: Dean (1922-2008) was a fruit grower who was a Saltfleet Township councillor (1948-1951) and then deputy reeve and reeve (1965-1973). He was one of the last wardens of Wentworth County and was the first mayor of the amalgamated Town of Stoney Creek in 1974. He served as mayor for six years and then was elected a Progressive Conservative MPP in 1981 for the old riding of Wentworth. He served as a minister in the governments of Bill Davis and Frank Miller. He quit politics in 1987.

211.name: Garner Road
211.desc: Hamilton Street Names says this part of the former Highway 53 in Ancaster was named after William B. Garner, who operated a blacksmith at the intersection of Southcote Road and Highway 53.
211.story: The first settlers arrived along the stretch of road in the 1790s. It was once called Methodist Row and also known as Sliding Church Road. This was due to a feud in what was then the Bowman Chapel (now Bowman United Church) between two Methodist sects. The log chapel was moved across boundary lines a number of times until calmer heads prevailed and it was left in the middle of the lot line.

212.name: Erland Falls
212.desc: The Stoney Creek falls is named after Erland Lee, who helped found the Womenâ€™s Institute with his wife Janet and Adelaide Hoodless in 1897.
212.story: The Lees founded the institute in a farmhouse on Ridge Road in Stoney Creek. It is now a museum and a National Historic Site of Canada. The falls is not too far from the museum. Institute members have campaigned for changes to benefit society, such as the pasteurization of milk, requiring traffic to stop when children are exiting school buses and the use of breathalyzers for suspected drunk drivers.

213.name: Felker's Falls Convservation Area
213.desc: The Stoney Creek conservation area and falls is named after a family which had the waterfall on their property.
213.story: The City of Waterfalls says the falls was owned by Joseph Benjamin Felker between 1880 and 1956.

214.name: Sherman Avenue
214.desc: Hamilton Street Names says the avenue is named after the first land assessor of the Hamilton district.
214.story: The avenue runs from the industrial section of Hamilton to Rymal Road on the east Mountain. It is called Upper Sherman on the mountain. The road was originally called Shearman Avenue, which was the last name of the land assessor.

215.name: Sherman Falls
215.desc: The Ancaster border is named after the Sherman family, which founded the Dominion Foundries and Steel Co. (Dofasco) in 1912.
215.story: The City of Waterfalls says the Sherman family was one of the families which owned the waterfall during the 20th Century. The waterfall was also once owned by the Whitton, Egleston and Smith family. Francis Whitton built a large home on land near the top of the waterfalls. It also is known by Fairy Falls and Angel Falls.

216.name: Sydenham Road
216.desc: Sydenham in both Dundas and Flamborough is believed to have been named after Charles Edward Poulett Thomson, Baron Sydenham of Sydenham and Toronto.
216.story: The baron was the Governor-in-Chief of Canada between 1839 and 1841. He was appointed to carry out the introduction of responsible government, introduce municipal institutions and unite Upper and Lower Canada. He was raised to the peerage for his efforts, but died in 1841 when he fell off his horse. He was unmarried and had no children, so the title died with him. Sydenham is a street in Dundas, but as it climbs up the Niagara Escarpment into Flamborough, it becomes a road.

217.name: McQuesten Park
217.desc: McQuesten is named after the prominent family that once lived in Whitehern, the city-owned museum-mansion on Jackson Street, behind Hamilton city hall.
217.story: Thomas B. McQuesten was born in 1882. He is perhaps best known as being the Minister of Public Works and Minister of Highways during the building and opening of the Queen Elizabeth Way in 1939. He served on Hamilton council and the Hamilton Board of Parks Management and helped the city attract McMaster University from Toronto and acquire Gage Park, Kingâ€™s Forest, Inch Park, the Chedoke Golf Course and the Royal Botanical Gardens. He died in 1948.

218.name: Henry and Beatrice Warden Park
218.desc: The east Hamilton-Stoney Creek park is named after the couple who used to own the land.
218.story: Henry and Beatrice Warden had a farm on the property. They bequeathed the property to the city upon their deaths. It was turned into a park in the late 1970s.

219.name: J.C. Beemer Park
219.desc: The Victorian Avenue North park is named after a Barton Street restaurant owner and union executive who was a volunteer on many Hamilton committees.
219.story: Jack Beemer served on the Hamilton Cemetery Board, the Board of Parks Management and the Playground Commission. He also served for decades as the federal returning officer for the old riding of Hamilton East and was active with the United Steelworkers of America. He was prominent in sports circles and organized the Moodie Tiger baseball team. He tried for a seat on city council four times between 1945 and 1973, but was unsuccessful. He died in 1995 at the age of 91.

220.name: James Smith Park
220.desc: The Ancaster park is named after a man who owned it and was one of the early settlers of Ancaster.
220.story: James Smith (1808-1884) was a descendant of John Smith, who came to Ancaster in 1789. He arrived from England in 1788, but first settled in Grimsby. James bought the land in 1853 and built a rare three-gabled limestone house on the property in 1860. The land and home were passed down to generations and it was eventually sold to developers in 1989. Stone from the house was saved and built into a cairn at the park. The park opened in 2002.

221.name: Joe Sams Park
221.desc: The Waterdown-area park was named after a former village reeve.
221.story: Joeseph Reed Sams (1923-2000) was a politician, soldier, insurance agent and community volunteer. He served with the Royal Hamilton Light Infantry 1943-1946 and was reeve of the village of Waterdown 1952-1961. He served as Wentworth County warden in 1958. He was elected the Progressive Conservative MP for Wentworth in 1962, but was defeated the following year. He ran unsuccessfully in the 1965 election. The Waterdown North Wetland Trails runs through part of the park.

222.name: John Prentice Park
222.desc: The Dundas park is named after John Prentice, who was a longtime Dundas and Hamilton-Wentworth regional councillor.
222.story: Prentice served as a Valley Town politician for 28 years. He was known as a plain-speaking, hard-working, no-nonsense advocate for Dundas. He was first elected in 1965 and only sat out a three-year period from council when he lost a bid to become mayor in 1985. He began serving on regional council in 1980. Prentice died at hospital in 1996, hours after suffering a stomach aneurysm at a council meeting. He was 69.

223.name: John Watson Park
223.desc: The Stoney Creek park is named after a man who served for more than a decade as the mayor of the old Town of Stoney Creek.
223.story: Watson, who was a professional engineer, served as a councillor on the old village council in 1955. He became reeve when Stoney Creek became a town in 1956 and then the next year was elected mayor. He served as mayor from 1959-1972. He suffered a stroke in 1971 and died in 1977.

224.name: Leslie B. Couldrey Park
224.desc: The Dundas park is named after a former mayor of the Valley Town.
224.story: Couldrey was born in England in 1889. He worked as a machinist after he came to Canada. He was first elected to Dundas council as deputy reeve in 1956 and became reeve in 1959. He was the first chair of the Spencer Creek Conservation Authority, which is now part of the Hamilton Conservation Authority, and was warden of Wentworth County in 1961. He became mayor in 1965 when Mayor Albert Edwards died in office. He served for two years. He died in 1986 at the age of 97.

225.name: Dr. William Bethune Park
225.desc: The Hamilton Mountain park is named after a well-known doctor who grew up in old Glanford Township and owned a farm on Upper James Street.
225.story: Bethune (1881-1953) graduated with his medical degree from the University of Toronto in 1907. He practiced in Hamilton between 1910-1914 and then went overseas to Europe as a doctor with the Canadian Expeditionary Force. After the war, he arranged the Department of Soldiers Civilian Re-establishment. He served for two decades as the chief of gynaecological services at Hamilton General Hospital. He also chaired the Barton Township school board and was active with the Boy Scouts. Bethune was the father of controller and alderman Jim Bethune (1929-2013) who served on council between 1962-1985.

226.name: Johnson Tew Park
226.desc: The Greensville park is named after a former Flamborough politician.
226.story: Johnson Tew was the Reeve of the Township of West Flamborough in the early 1900s. He served as Warden of Wentworth County in 1926.

227.name: Morgan Firestone Arena
227.desc: The Ancaster arena was named after the grandson of Harvey Firestone, the founder of the famous tire company.
227.story: Born in Akron, Ohio, in 1930, Morgan Firestone came to Hamilton in 1965 to become vice-president of Firestoneâ€™s Canadian operations. He left in 1970 to found the Firan Corp., which made electronics for air traffic controls and a producer of recreational vehicles. The Ancaster resident was well-known as a philanthropist and supported 35 charities. He died in 2009.

228.name: John Willson Park
228.desc: The Winona Park is named after a member of one the first families to settle in the former Saltfleet area in the 1790s.
228.story: John Willson (1776-1860) was a farmer, judge and politician. He was first elected to the assembly in 1809 and served pretty well uninterrupted until 1834. One of his contemporaries was Sir Allan MacNab. He also served as a judge, a school board trustee and as a director on the Welland Canal Company. The Dictionary of Hamilton Biography notes his importance by pointing out that more than 100 carriages attended his funeral.

229.name: Leckie Park Neighbourhood
229.desc: The Upper Stoney Creek neighbourhood is named after the former longtime chief engineer for the city of Hamilton, Campbell Leckie.
229.story: Leckie was born in Glasgow in 1848. The Dictionary of Hamilton Biography says he became a marine engineer on ships on the Atlantic and settled in Hamilton in 1873. He worked as an engineer at the Grand Truck Railway shops. He joined the city in 1897 and worked his way up to become chief engineer in 1904. He served in that job for 18 years. Leckie died in 1925.

230.name: Beasley Neighbourhood
230.desc: The downtown neighbourhood is named for the Beasley family, one of the first settlers to the Hamilton area (then Head of the Lake) in the 1790s. It is bound by Barton Street, James Street, King Street and Wellington Street.
230.story: Richard Beasley (1761-1842) came to Niagara in the 1780s as an United Empire Loyalist fleeing the upheaval in New York caused by the American Revolution. A merchant, judge and Reform politician, he settled on Burlington Heights (the present day home of Dundurn Castle) in 1793. His son Henry (1793-1859) served in the local militia during the War of 1812 and became Hamiltonâ€™s first treasurer in 1844.

231.name: Vincent Neighbourhood
231.desc: The east Hamilton neighbourhood is named after John Vincent, a British army officer who served in the Hamilton-Niagara area during the War of 1812. It is bound by King Street, Greenhill Avenue and Mount Albion Road.
231.story: Vincent (1764-1848) was a brigadier-general who retreated from Fort George to Burlington Heights when a large force of Americans attacked in May 1813. He approved sending a force from the heights to Stoney Creek to attack an American encampment. The Americans retreated after heavy casualties and having two of their commanding generals captured. Vincent later served as commander of the garrisons in Kingston and Montreal.

232.name: Gibson Neighbourhood
232.desc: The central Hamilton street and area is named after Sir John Morison Gibson, who was the first Hamiltonian to serve as Lieutenant Governor of Ontario (1908-1914)
232.story: Gibson was also one of â€œThe four Johnsâ€ who built the first hydroelectric plant in Canada at DeCew Falls in Niagara and brought hydro-electric power to Hamilton. He was born in 1842 near Toronto and came to Hamilton when he was a child. He excelled at school and had many other achievements, such as serving on many company boards, turning on the water of Hamiltonâ€™s new waterworks in 1859, fighting in the Battle of Ridgeway in 1866 and founding the Childrenâ€™s Aid Society, the Hamilton Law Association, the Canadian Red Cross and the Wentworth Historical Society. He died in 1929.

233.name: Trenholme Neighbourhood
233.desc: These two neighbourhoods honour Clementina Trenholme Fessenden, who founded Empire Day (now Victoria Day) in 1899 and helped establish the Soldiersâ€™ Monument at Stoney Creek in 1913. Fessenden is on the west Mountain and is bound by Upper Paradise Road, the Lincoln M. Alexander Parkway and Mohawk Road. Trenholme is on the east Mountain and is bound by Limeridge Road, Pritchard Road, the Lincoln M. Alexander Parkway and Upper Ottawa Street.
233.story: Clementina came to Ancaster in 1895 with her husband Elisha Joseph Fessenden when he was appointed rector of St. Johnâ€™s Anglican Church. Her husband died in 1896. She became interested in holding Empire Day due to tales of pioneer days told to her grand-daughter. She promoted it through the Imperial Order of the Daughters of the Empire (IODE) and the first Empire Day was celebrated in Hamilton in 1899. It started spreading through other British realms in 1904. Fessenden died in Hamilton in 1918.

234.name: Fessenden Neighbourhood
234.desc: These two neighbourhoods honour Clementina Trenholme Fessenden, who founded Empire Day (now Victoria Day) in 1899 and helped establish the Soldiersâ€™ Monument at Stoney Creek in 1913. Fessenden is on the west Mountain and is bound by Upper Paradise Road, the Lincoln M. Alexander Parkway and Mohawk Road. Trenholme is on the east Mountain and is bound by Limeridge Road, Pritchard Road, the Lincoln M. Alexander Parkway and Upper Ottawa Street.
234.story: Clementina came to Ancaster in 1895 with her husband Elisha Joseph Fessenden when he was appointed rector of St. Johnâ€™s Anglican Church. Her husband died in 1896. She became interested in holding Empire Day due to tales of pioneer days told to her grand-daughter. She promoted it through the Imperial Order of the Daughters of the Empire (IODE) and the first Empire Day was celebrated in Hamilton in 1899. It started spreading through other British realms in 1904. Fessenden died in Hamilton in 1918.

235.name: Doug Wright Park
235.desc: Doug Wright (1917 to 1983) was a popular Canadian cartoonist who lived in Burlington from the mid-1960s onward.
235.story: Wright was best known for his weekly comic strip Doug Wright's Family, also known as Nipper. The strip, about a suburban family, began in 1949 for the Montreal Standard newspaper before gaining widespread exposure in Weekend Magazine, which used to be inserted into many Saturday newspapers in Canada. Wright also drew comic strips Max & Mini, Cynthia and The Wheels, as well as producing editorial cartoons at The Spectator.

236.name: Walker's Line
236.desc: The route is named for Philip Walker, who, with his wife, Susannah Cline, was an early settler in the area.
236.story: The Walkers arrived in 1816 and grew to a family of 10, acquiring more land for farming as new families were formed, according to the Burlington Historical Society.

237.name: Phoebe Crescent
237.desc: The crescent is named after the youngest daughter of Robert and Phoebe Land, early settlers in the area.
237.story: Phoebe Land married Clement Lucas, a ship carpenter in New Brunswick and she died a short time after their marriage, according to the Burlington Historical Society.

238.name: Spencer Smith Park
238.desc: Spencer Smith (1870 to 1955) was a former president of the Burlington Horticultural Society and a key figure in developing the park that would later be named for him.
238.story: Smith owned a grocery and fresh produce store on Brant Street and was a hard-working volunteer with the horticultural society, pushing to have trees planted on Burlington streets. In his retirement, he focused attention on creating the waterfront park at the bottom of that same street.

239.name: Bellwood Avenue
239.desc: The street is named for the Bell family, which operated an orchard in the area.
239.story: According to the Burlington Historical Society, Fred Bell was a shoemaker on Brant Street, who bought the land in 1875 and became a farmer. He lived there with his two brothers and two sisters and operated Bell Orchards. The orchard eventually passed to his nephew Robert Allen, and then to his son, John Allen. The street was named for the family when homes were built on the property in the late 1940s. It is not far from downtown Burlington and is in the Brant neighbourhood.

240.name: Nelson Avenue
240.desc: It is named for Admiral Horatio Nelson, the hero of the 1805 Battle of Trafalgar. The sea battle was fought off the coast of Spain between the Royal Navy and the combined French forces of the Emperor Napoleon and the Spanish navy. The British victory confirmed British supremacy of the sea well into the 20th century.
240.story: According to the book Burlington's Streets, an 1874 subdivision plan by Benjamin Eager laid out Nelson Avenue. The avenue was located in what was then Nelson Township. The township was named for the admiral in 1806; Burlington annexed Nelson Township in 1958.

241.name: Beaver Street
241.desc: It is believed to have been named for the animal that has become a symbol of Canada and still builds dams in the region.
241.story: The book Burlington's Streets says the street was named to honour the beaver, which has long been associated with the Hudson Bay Company (appeared on its coat of arms in 1678), has appeared on the nickel, on stamps and was part of the logo for CP Rail. The book notes the 1869 map of Port Nelson shows the street. In 1975, Parliament voted to designate the beaver as Canada's national animal. The act was introduced by Hamilton-Wentworth Tory MP Sean O'Sullivan.

242.name: Bavaront Place
242.desc: The street was named by engineer George Schneider in 1949, when he built a home in Halton Place, a new subdivision. He originally used Bavaront to name his house â€” which then carried onto the street.
242.story: Bavaront is a combination of the two birthplaces of Schneider and his wife, Jaqueline, according to the book Burlington's Streets. He was born in Bavaria; his wife in Ontario.

243.name: Secord Lane
243.desc: Laura Secord (1775 to 1868) is remembered for having walked 32 kilometres out of U.S.-occupied territory in 1813 to warn British forces of an American plan to attack.
243.story: Secord Lane is a private road on property once awarded to Laura Secord, according to the book Burlington Streets, What's Behind a Name? However, she never lived on the land.

244.name: Smith Avenue
244.desc: Maxwell Smith was the first mayor of Burlington, serving from 1915 to 1916.
244.story: From 1908 to 1915, he was reeve of the village of Burlington. After it was proclaimed a town, he became Burlington's first mayor. According to the book Burlington Streets: What's Behind a Name? Smith is also credited by some with having come up with the idea of painting a centre line on roadways to try to keep oncoming automobiles from colliding.

245.name: Penny Lane
245.desc: According to Ron Deppner, the road was named after his mother, Penny Deppner, who died in 1987 at the age of 44 from a brain aneurysm. His dad, Ron, was a developer and put through the paperwork to have the street named in Penny's honour.
245.story: At the time of her death, an article ran in The Spectator noting how various organ donations from her allowed five others to live. 'I don't believe The Beatles song was a factor' in calling it Penny Lane rather than Penny Avenue or something else, says Ron.

246.name: Palmer Drive
246.desc: Charles Palmer, who arrived in 1906, farmed land in the area for nearly five decades.
246.story: Palmer also worked for the federal Department of Agriculture and served on Nelson Township Council and the Burlington Suburban Planning Board, according to the Burlington Historical Society book Burlington Streets.

247.name: Pearson Street
247.desc: Lester Bowles (Mike) Pearson (1897 to 1972) was Canadaâ€™s 14th prime minister.
247.story: As well as serving as PM from 1963 to â€™68, Pearson won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1957 for putting together the United Nations Emergency Force to resolve the Suez Canal Crisis. He was a professor, civil servant and diplomat as well as a politician. His government is remembered for universal health care, student loan and the Canada Pension plan legislation and for changing the countryâ€™s flag to the red maple leaf we all know so well.

248.name: M.M. Robinson High School
248.desc: The school was named after Melville Marks (Bobby) Robinson (1888 to 1974), who is best known for founding the British Empire Games, later known as the Commonwealth Games.
248.story: Robinson was a well-liked man of many accomplishments. He was sports editor of this newspaper in 1930 when he founded the Games and was later inducted into the Sports Hall of Fame. He was also a Burlington area fruit farmer who founded the Ontario Food Council, and served as chair of the Burlington Board of Education.

249.name: Bartok Road
249.desc: The road is named for the great Hungarian composer Bela Bartok (1881 to 1945).
249.story: According to the book Burlingtonâ€™s Street Names by the Burlington Historical Society, the road was named after Bartok in 1986 when the area opened to residential development. Bartok, who also wrote two ballets and an opera also collected folk music in the hinterland of Hungary in the early 20th century. He came to the United States in 1940 and died of complications of leukemia in New York City five years later.

250.name: Pepper Drive
250.desc: Relatives of two local farmers, Agustino Bedini and Peter Dell, say the work of their ancestors holds the history for this street.
250.story: According to the book Burlingtonâ€™s Streets, by the Burlington Historical Society, this area was the sandy soil of the market gardens until the 1950s, where some of the best peppers in Ontario grew. The pepper patches were produced by two local farmers. The street named for their efforts was developed in 1954.

251.name: Addison Street
251.desc: William and Isabel Addison came to Canada from England in the 1830s, eventually settling in what later became the city of Burlington.
251.story: The family lived in a log house on a farm west of Brant Street. Kerns Road passes through the former Addison homestead, according to the book Burlington Streets by Peggy and Les Armstrong.

252.name: Robert Bateman High School
252.desc: Robert Bateman, who used to live in Burlington, is a world-renowned wildlife painter.
252.story: Bateman was a teacher in Burlington before his art career took off. He now lives on Saltspring Island in British Columbia. As well as the school, Bateman Court, off Greenwood Drive, in Burlington is named after the artist.

253.name: Nicholson Court
253.desc: It is named for the Nicholson family. They ran a lumber business in Burlington from 1908 until the late 1990s.
253.story: The street and development was built about 1978, according to Burlingtonâ€™s Streets by the Burlington Historical Society. The land was, for many years, the lakefront estate of both A.S. Nicholson and his son, Warren Nicholson. The two families shared the stately home which stood on the property.

254.name: Berryman Court
254.desc: The street is named for Lloyd Berryman, who was on Burlington council and served as mayor in 1966 and 1967 â€” Canadaâ€™s Centennial Year.
254.story: Berryman was born in Hamilton in 1921 and served as an RCAF fighter pilot during the Second World War. He earned the Distinguished Flying Cross in 1944 for shooting down three enemy aircraft with his Spitfire in one day and, in 2007, was one of 50 Canadians given Franceâ€™s highest decoration, the Legion of Honour. He flew 135 missions. Berryman moved to Burlington in 1950 and served as a town councillor from 1964 to 1965 before being elected mayor. He argued unsuccessfully that Burlington should be part of the then-Region of Hamilton-Wentworth. Berryman died in April 2012 at the age of 90.

255.name: Unsworth Avenue
255.desc: It is named for the Unsworth family, who came to the area in 1848 from Liverpool.
255.story: Giles Gorton Unsworth and his wife, Ann, arrived with a family of nine, according to the book Burlingtonâ€™s Streets by the Burlington Historical Society. The couple died within three years. The first Unsworth farm was north of Plains Road, where Sumach Drive is now. In 1882, family member Albert bought land south of that on Plains Road. His son, George Unsworth, built his first greenhouse in 1900. Its heat plant with a clock later became an Aldershot landmark. The greenhouses were demolished in 2005. The Burlington Gardens retirement home was built on the property in 2007.

256.name: Torrance Street
256.desc: The street is named for the Torrance family, who were merchant shippers based in Montreal.
256.story: The street was established in 1878, according to Burlingtonâ€™s Streets by the Burlington Historical Society. The Torrance family purchased land that contained the street off James Gage decades earlier. David Torrance filed two survey plans in the 1870s. Another survey was done in 1884. David Torrance, who had been president of the Bank of Montreal, died in 1876.

257.name: Roly Bird Park
257.desc: Bird was mayor of Burlington from 1979-1991. He died in January 2004 at the age of 73.
257.story: Bird grew up on a farm outside Fredericton, N.B. When he was 17 he moved to Ontario to work as a welder at Westinghouse in Hamilton and later as an insurance underwriter. After serving as alderman, he took a shot at the mayorâ€™s seat in 1973 and lost. Then on his second attempt in the municipal election in 1978 he won. He stayed in the job for 12 years becoming the longest serving mayor in Burlingtonâ€™s history.

258.name: McKinstry Street
258.desc: Henry McKinstry (1805 to 1871) was mayor of Hamilton from 1859 to 1861.
258.story: While McKinstry was mayor, His Royal Highness Edward, Prince of Wales spent time in Hamilton as part of a royal visit to Canada. The whirlwind visit saw the prince dedicate Hamiltonâ€™s new waterworks and declare the provincial exhibition open at the cityâ€™s Crystal Palace.

259.name: Earl Kitchener
259.desc: The school is named for Horatio Herbert Kitchener, a British field marshal who gained fame for his imperial campaigns in the Sudan in the 1890s.
259.story: Built in 1915, Earl Kitchener is one of the cityâ€™s oldest schools still in operation. Today, the school houses students from kindergarten to Grade 5 and hosts several unique programs, including French immersion and the public school boardâ€™s popular violin and piano programs.

260.name: Bullock's Corners
260.desc: It is named for the family of William Bullock, who came to Hamilton in 1833.
260.story: The family became involved in various parts of the areaâ€™s development. William Bullock opened a tavern called the British Hotel in 1837 which served people travelling by stagecoach between Dundas and Guelph. The tavern became the centre of the community, with a general store and a blacksmith opening before 1840. Bullock served on West Flamborough Township council from 1852-1855.

261.name: Harvey Falls
261.desc: Wes Harvey bought a parcel of land in the 1800s that included the falls.
261.story: Harvey Falls is one of an estimated 126 waterfalls in Hamilton. It is located on private property but can be seen from the Bruce Trail, from McNeilly or Fifty Road.

262.name: Strabane, Ont.
262.desc: The community was once called Nairn, after a village in Scotland. When it was learned there was another community with that name in Canada West in the mid-19th Century, Irish settlers decided to name the hamlet for a community in their homeland.
262.story: The hamlet began developing in the early 1840s with the construction of two small mills. Within two decades, Strabane also had a hotel, saddlery, carpenterâ€™s shop, stone mason and general store. There was a large stable behind the hotel. It was used for changing horses on the coach ride between Dundas and Guelph.

263.name: George R. Allen
263.desc: George R. Allan (1860-1940) worked for 60 years at The Spectator and for 36 years as a public board of education trustee.
263.story: Allan served as a trustee during a time that saw a rapid modernization of schools in Hamilton. In 1927, a school seen to be among the most modern of the era was named after him. Allanâ€™s brother John (1856-1922) was a mayor of Hamilton and a member of the provincial Parliament.

264.name: Chedoke Golf Course
264.desc: Chedoke is not only the name of a city-owned golf course, but a street, an expressway, a falls, a school, a pool and many businesses use it as well.
264.story: What exactly is a Chedoke? Some think it is a native word meaning 'big healing place.'' But according to the book Indian Place Names in the Province of Ontario by W.F. Moore, the real story is a little more complicated. He writes that Chedoke is a mispronunciation of the English words 'Seven Oaks,' a name used by settlers to describe a section of property near Garth Street and Fennell Avenue West that had seven big oak trees.

265.name: Aikman Avenue
265.desc: John Aikman (1764-1841) was a United Empire Loyalist who settled with his wife, Hannah (Showers), in the area in 1787. The family lived near what is now King Street and Sanford Avenue.
265.story: John and his three sons, Alexander (1790-1876), John (1791-1878) and Michael (1796-1881), took part in the battles of Queenston Heights and Lundyâ€™s Lane in the War of 1812. Alexander Aikman is believed to be the first non-native child to be born in what later became known as Hamilton.

266.name: Aikman Avenue
266.desc: It was named for a town in Vermont
266.story: The community was first settled in the 1840s and was originally called Vansickle after a local family. According to the 1970 book Ancaster's Heritage, a meeting was held in 1852 in a log school house to give the settlement a new name. Jeremiah Bishop (1795-1885), who came to the area in 1816 from Vermont, suggested naming it after a 'pretty little town' called Lynden not far from his hometown of St. Johnsbury. The gathering approved, and Lynden was born.

267.name: Viscount Montgomery Elementary School
267.desc: Field Marshal Viscount Montgomery of Alamein (1887 â€” 1976) was a prominent military leader in the Second World War, also with a distinguished service record in the First World War.
267.story: Montgomery referred to the school as his 'beloved school,' and visited it five times. According to the Hamilton-Wentworth District School Board, he told students during his last visit in 1960: 'Let's make Viscount Montgomery School the best in Hamilton, the best in Ontario, the best in Canada. I don't associate myself with anything that is not good. It is up to you to see that everything about this school is good. It is up to the students to not only be the best in school, but in their behaviour outside of Viscount. Education is not just something that will help you pass your exams and get you a job, it is to develop your brain to teach you to marshal facts and do things.

268.name: Valens
268.desc: It is named for the Valens family which settled in the area in 1834.
268.story: John Valens was the first settler in the area. That is from the 1889 book The Pioneers of Beverly. His brother Robert and sister Jane also came to the area. The book mentions how John Valens also brought the first threshing machine into the settlement and built the first saw mill. The farm community honoured him with the title of 'Governor.' He was one of the first men elected to Beverly Township Council in 1850. Valens (1810-1894) is buried in Kirkwall.

269.name: Bellwood Avenue
269.desc: The street is named for the Bell family, which operated an orchard in the area.
269.story: According to the Burlington Historical Society, Fred Bell was a shoemaker on Brant Street, who bought the land in 1875 and became a farmer. He lived there with his two brothers and two sisters and operated Bell Orchards. The orchard eventually passed to his nephew Robert Allen, and then to his son, John Allen. The street was named for the family when homes were built on the property in the late 1940s. It is not far from downtown Burlington and is in the Brant neighbourhood.

270.name: Stewart Lane
270.desc: James Stewart from Waterdown was a teacher at the schoolhouse in Millgrove starting in 1895.
270.story: According to the book Hamilton Street Names, the street was named to honour 'Jim,' who was instrumental in establishing the community's first library, and the Millgrove Literary and Debating Society in 1903.

271.name: Stewart Lane
271.desc: It was named for Mary Smith, one of the area's first settlers.
271.story: According to the book Exploring Niagara, Smith was the wife of Richard Griffin. The couple and their dozen children came to the area from New York State in 1787 after the American Revolution. They settled on three lots along the Twenty Mile Creek. The settlement was first called Griffintown, but was later renamed Smithville. It is the administrative centre of West Lincoln.

272.name: Winona
272.desc: It is not clear where the name came from.
272.story: The community was called Ontario when the post office opened in 1851. It was changed to Winona in 1868, a year after Confederation, because Canada West was renamed Ontario. According to Saltfleet Then and Now, some said the community was renamed Winona because of the vineyards, while others said it was named after the daughter of Chief Tecumseh. Ontario Place Names says it means 'first-born daughter' and that the chief's daughter is believed to have jumped to her death from the Niagara Escarpment.

273.name: Lisgar School
273.desc: It is named for Sir John Lisgar, one of the countryâ€™s earliest governors general.
273.story: Lisgar, previously a lawyer, was Canadaâ€™s second GG, serving from 1869 to 1872, at which time he returned to his native Ireland. The Hamilton school â€” one of several in the country to honour him â€” opened in 1964.

274.name: Lewis Road
274.desc: Levi Lewis (1762 to 1828) was a United Empire Loyalist who came to the Grimsby area in 1787 with his family from New Jersey.
274.story: Lewis worked as a farmer and politician in pre-Confederation Canada. From 1808 to 1812, he served in the Legislative Assembly of Upper Canada. His son, also named Levi, was a reeve of Saltfleet Township. The family built what came to be known as Lewis House on Lewis Road.

275.name: Limeridge Road
275.desc: Limeridge is a reference to a limestone ridge on the Mountain near where Limeridge Road runs today.
275.story: Through the mid 1800s into the mid 1900s, limestone was quarried from the area, most notably by the Marshall and Gallagher families, according to the book Hamilton Street Names, an Illustrated Guide by Margaret Houghton.

276.name: Southampton Boulevard
276.desc: Southampton Boulevard is a busy entryway into Burlington's Headon Forest neighbourhood, off Walker's Line just south of Dundas Street.
276.story: According to the book Burlington's Streets, the road built in 1989 was named Southampton because it was an 'entry port' into the newly built neighbourhood. Southhampton in England was a busy shipping port and was home to the White Star Line. It's also the port where the Mayflower set sail in 1620.

277.name: James MacDonald School
277.desc: MacDonald, who died in 1985 at the age of 80, was a longtime municipal politician and school board trustee.
277.story: He served as a school board trustee and as its chair, and as a Barton township councillor. Then, after Barton was annexed by Hamilton in 1960, he ran as a City of Hamilton alderman. He was re-elected continuously after that until his retirement in 1982.

278.name: James MacDonald School
278.desc: The street is named in tribute to the Leeming family, who emigrated to Canada from England in the early 1800s.
278.story: Reverend Ralph Leeming was the first rector of St. Johnâ€™s Anglican Church in Ancaster, and his brother William Leeming became the rector of Trinity Church at Chippawa. Their brother, Braithwaite, followed later on and obtained land in Glanford, where he married Phoebe Land, the daughter of one of Hamiltonâ€™s first settlers.

279.name: Jones Road
279.desc: Jones Road is named for a family which came to the area in 1789 and whose patriarch surveyed what was then Saltfleet Township.
279.story: Augustus Jones was born in New York State circa 1763 and was appointed deputy surveyor. According to Saltfleet Then and Now 1792-1973, he was given 485 hectares of land in Saltfleet after he set up it for settlers into lots and concessions. He married a native chiefâ€™s daughter in 1798 and they had 10 children. He served with the 5th Lincoln Regiment during the War of 1812 and died in 1836. He had seven siblings who settled in Saltfleet and a brother, Ebenezer, also worked as a land surveyor.

280.name: Ferguson Avenue
280.desc: Peter Ferguson came to the area with his wife, Florence, in the 1790s, and was one of the first settlers in the Head of the Lake.
280.story: He was given 100 acres of land between Main Street and the Bay around where Ferguson Avenue is today. Through the 1800s and into the early 1900s, Ferguson Avenue had a major train station for trains passing through the city.

281.name: The Bill Sturrup Media and Community Room
281.desc: Bill Sturrup was a broadcaster in Hamilton for more than 45 years who died in 2007 at the age of 68.
281.story: Sturrup worked at 900 CHML as a reporter but was well known for covering sports. He also regularly worked as a public address announcer at professional and amateur sporting events in Hamilton that included Hamilton Bulldogs, Hamilton Cardinals and Hamilton Tiger-Cats games.

282.name: Hendrie Gate
282.desc: William Hendrie (1831 to 1906) founded a successful freight hauling company and was known for horse breeding.
282.story: In 1931, a century after Hendrieâ€™s birth, his family donated 49 hectares of land that became the Royal Botanical Gardens. At the same time, the family commissioned â€œa magnificent set of wrought iron gates, to be used in constructing an entrance marker to Hendrie Park.â€

283.name: Helen Detwiler School
283.desc: Detwiler was a teacher, trustee and a former chair of the Hamilton Board of Education who died in 1991 at the age of 80.
283.story: Detwiler gave nearly 60 years of her life to education as a teacher at several Hamilton schools until her retirement in 1970. After that she became a trustee for Ward 7, serving as chair in 1981.

284.name: Helen Detwiler School
284.desc: Lee (1862 to 1940) and Adelaide Hoodless were cofounders of the Womenâ€™s Institute, which promoted the education of isolated rural women by offering courses in areas such as cooking, sewing, home nutrition, child care and handicrafts. The concept spread around the world.
284.story: Lee was also a teacher who taught the first kindergarten class in Hamilton. Janet Lee Elementary School opened in 1987.

285.name: Mary Hopkins Elementary School
285.desc: Hopkins was the first teacher in Waterdown. Hopkins gave her classes in a schoolhouse built from logs in 1815 at the corner of Mill and Dundas streets.
285.story: In July 1964, the name of the Mill Street school that first opened in January 1921 was changed to Mary Hopkins.

286.name: Lower and Upper Horning Road
286.desc: The roads are named for the Horning family, who came to this area from Pennsylvania in the 1780s.
286.story: Patriarch Peter Horning, born in 1740, came to the area in 1789, following in the footsteps of his sons, Isaac and Abraham. Peter became a large landholder in Hamilton. Both of his sons settled and farmed in the western part of Barton Township, which once encircled Hamilton like a horseshoe. The last of the township was annexed by the city in 1960 and faded into history.

287.name: Aldershot
287.desc: It is not exactly clear how the community got its name. According to Ontario Place Names, a post office opened in 1856 under the name Aldershott. It is also believed settler William Applegarth gave the community its name. His family came to the area in the 1790s.
287.story: Ontario Place Names says it was first settled in 1783 by David Fonger and was known as Brownâ€™s Wharf after a landing built by a Colonel Brown in the 1840s. It was also called Burlington Plains, and Port Flamborough at some point. Aldershot was part of East Flamborough Township until 1958, when it was sliced off and amalgamated along with Nelson Township into the Town of Burlington.

288.name: Peter Street Trail
288.desc: Peter Street was a watch repair person and later worked as community relations director at Amity Goodwill. He died at the age of 46 in 1984.
288.story: Street had a rare congenital bone disease that caused him to suffer numerous bone fractures when he was a boy and led to him having to use a wheelchair. He was well-liked, inspiring and did much to raise awareness about issues that affect people with disabilities. (Item suggested by reader Richard Segee.)

289.name: Hamilton
289.desc: George Hamilton (1788-1836), who fought in the War of 1812, was a merchant and politician credited with founding Hamilton.
289.story: The community was conceived by George Hamilton, who purchased land holdings from James Durand after the War of 1812. From there the community at the head of Lake Ontario grew to a town and then finally was incorporated as a city in 1846.
